<DOC><DOCNO> DOE2-16-0406 </DOCNO><TEXT>In unusually frank terms the author, a journalist and epidemiologist,describes the catastrophe of Chernobyl as the 'most pathetic and important'experience of the Soviet people after World War II. Documents, interviewsand statements of persons concerned trace the disaster of those daysthat surpasses imagination and describe how individual persons witnessedthe coming true of visions of terror. (orig./HSCH).</TEXT></DOC>